  "prompt": "Why does the RBI increase the repo rate during inflation and decrease it during deflation?",
  "response": "The Reserve Bank of India (RBI) adjusts the **repo rate**\u2014the rate at which it lends money to commercial banks\u2014to manage inflation and deflation, as part of its monetary policy. Here\u2019s why the RBI increases the repo rate during inflation and decreases it during deflation:\n\n### During Inflation:\nInflation refers to a sustained increase in the general price level of goods and services over time. When inflation is high, the purchasing power of money decreases. To control inflation, the RBI **increases the repo rate**:\n\n1. **Higher Borrowing Costs**: An increase in the repo rate makes borrowing more expensive for commercial banks. This, in turn, leads to higher interest rates for consumers and businesses.\n2. **Reduced Spending**: Higher borrowing costs discourage people and businesses from taking loans, leading to reduced spending and investment.\n3. **Decreased Money Supply**: Lower spending reduces the demand for goods and services, which helps to bring down prices and stabilize inflation.\n4. **Encourages Savings**: Higher interest rates incentivize saving rather than spending, reducing the money circulating in the economy.\n\n### During Deflation:\nDeflation is a sustained decrease in the general price level of goods and services, often leading to reduced economic activity. To combat deflation, the RBI **decreases the repo rate**:\n\n1. **Lower Borrowing Costs**: A reduction in the repo rate makes borrowing cheaper for commercial banks, which lowers interest rates for consumers and businesses.\n2. **Increased Spending**: Lower borrowing costs encourage people and businesses to take loans, leading to increased spending and investment.\n3. **Increased Money Supply**: Higher spending boosts demand for goods and services, which helps to increase prices and stimulate economic activity.\n4. **Discourages Savings**: Lower interest rates discourage saving and encourage spending, increasing the money circulating in the economy.\n\n### Summary:\n- **Increase in Repo Rate during Inflation**: Reduces money supply, curbs spending, and stabilizes prices.\n- **Decrease in Repo Rate during Deflation**: Increases money supply, boosts spending, and stimulates economic growth.\n\nBy adjusting the repo rate, the RBI aims to maintain price stability and support sustainable economic growth.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
